   options = {
      columnnames = {'d', 'd'},
      rownames = {'a', 'b', 'a'},
   },
}
```

Looking at the message that is being broadcast at https://github.com/facebookresearch/visdom/blob/master/py/server.py#L220 (`p`), everything still appears to be fine:
```
{u'title': u'', u'i': 0, u'contentID': '34ef28ecaef900', u'content': {'layout': {u'margin': {u'r': 60, u'b': 60, u't': 60, u'l': 60}}, 'data': [{u'zmax': 1.0054633722786, u'colorscale': u'Viridis', u'zmin': -1.4410649905944, u'y': [u'a', u'b', u'a'], u'x': [u'd', u'd'], u'z': [[-0.50443826056116, -0.55385051210768], [-0.52712315391279, 1.0054633722786], [-1.4410649905944, 0.50761805140936]], u'type': u'heatmap'}]}, u'command': u'pane', u'type': u'plot', u'id': u'pane_34ef28ecaef8ba'}
```

Which suggests this must be happening in the rendering. Indeed, others appear to have observed the same issue: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/40742473/plotly-seems-to-lose-labels-of-a-heatmap

I'm afraid I don't have a good work-around for this at the moment (other than not using duplicate labels).

The Python line that lead to this is nothing special: `pose = Pose()` where Pose class is bound like this:

```C++
pybind11::class_<core::pose::Pose, std::shared_ptr<core::pose::Pose>> cl(M("core::pose"), "Pose", "...");
pybind11::handle cl_type = cl;
cl.def(pybind11::init<>());
cl.def(pybind11::init<const class core::pose::Pose &>(), pybind11::arg("src"));
cl.def(pybind11::init<const class core::pose::Pose &, unsigned long, unsigned long>(), pybind11::arg("src"), pybind11::arg("residue_begin"), pybind11::arg("residue_end"));
...
```

